04161nam a22006615i 9780857458711DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20002000nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574587117 a10.1515/97808574587112doi  a(DE-B1597)636783  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDA880.B72bG73 2011 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a941.3/70852231 aGray, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAt Home in the Hills :bSense of Place in the Scottish Borders /cJohn Gray. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2000] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tPREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION: Place-Making and Family Farms in the Scottish Borders -- tChapter 1. REIVERS OF THE MARCHES -- tChapter 2. TENANTS ON LANDED ESTATES -- tChapter 3. SHEEP FARMING IN THE COMMUNITY -- tChapter 4. FORMS OF TENURE -- tChapter 5. SHEEP AND LAND -- tChapter 6. HILL SHEEP AND TUPS -- tChapter 7. LAMB AUCTIONS -- tChapter 8. RAM AUCTIONS -- tChapter 9. THE BIG HOUSE -- tChapter 10. THE FARMHOUSE -- tAFTERWORD -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTo most outsiders, the hills of the Scottish Borders are a bleak and foreboding space - usually made to represent the stigmatized Other, Ad Finis, by the centers of power in Edinburgh, London, and Brussels. At a time when globalization seems to threaten our sense of place, people of the Scottish borderlands provide a vivid case study of how the being-in-place is central to the sense of self and identity. Since the end of the thirteenth century, people living in the Scottish Border hills have engaged in armed raiding on the frontier with England, developed capitalist sheep farming in the newly united kingdom of Great Britain, and are struggling to maintain their family farms in one of the marginal agricultural rural regions of the European Community. Throughout their history, sheep farmers living in these hills have established an abiding sense of place in which family and farm have become refractions of each other. Adopting a phenomenological perspective, this book concentrates on the contemporary farming practices - shepherding, selling lambs and rams at auctions - as well as family and class relations through which hill sheep fuse people, place, and way of life to create this sense of being-at-home in the hills.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aAgriculturezScotlandzScottish BordersxHistoryy20th century. 0aFamilieszScotlandzScottish BordersxHistoryy20th century. 0aFarm lifezScotlandzScottish BordersxHistoryy20th century. 0aLandlord and tenantzScotlandzScottish BordersxHistoryy20th century. 0aRural familieszScotlandzScottish BordersxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978085745871140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780857458711423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780857458711/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK